is clubbing of his fingers. Fine basal crepitations are auscultated across both lung fields.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate test to confirm the probable diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest X-ray","Lung biopsy","High resolution CT chest","Peak flow measurements","Pulmonary function testing"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate test to confirm the probable diagnosis of interstitial lung disease (ILD) in this patient is a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh resolution CT chest\u003C/strong\u003E. This imaging modality provides detailed images of the lung parenchyma and is superior to a chest X-ray in diagnosing ILD, as it can detect subtle interstitial changes that may not be visible on a standard X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is often the initial imaging test performed, but it has limited sensitivity and specificity for ILD. It may miss early or mild interstitial changes, which is why a high resolution CT is preferred for confirmation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elung biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E can provide a definitive diagnosis by allowing histopathological examination of lung tissue. However, it is invasive and carries risks, making it less desirable as an initial diagnostic test, especially when non-invasive options like high resolution CT are available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeak flow measurements\u003C/strong\u003E assess airway obstruction and are not useful for diagnosing ILD, which primarily affects the lung interstitium rather than the airways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary function testing\u003C/strong\u003E can provide information about lung volumes and gas exchange, which may suggest restrictive lung disease consistent with ILD. However, it does not provide specific information about the lung parenchyma and is not used to confirm the diagnosis of ILD.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A high resolution CT is the preferred diagnostic investigation for suspected interstitial lung disease.","Occupational exposure and certain medications, such as amiodarone, are risk factors for interstitial lung disease."],"references":["Mikolasch TA, Garthwaite HS, Porter JC. Update in diagnosis and management of interstitial lung disease\u2002. Clin Med (Lond). 2017 Apr;17(2):146-153. doi: 10.7861/clinmedicine.17-2-146. PMID: 28365626; PMCID: PMC6297625. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28365626/","Rea G, Bocchino M. The challenge of diagnosing interstitial lung disease by HRCT: state of the art and future perspectives. J Bras Pneumol. 2021 Jun 23;47(3):e20210199. doi: 10.36416/1806-3756/e20210199. PMID: 34190867; PMCID: PMC8332719. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8332719/","Nathan SD, Pastre J, Ksovreli I, Barnett S, King C, Aryal S, Ahmad K, Fukuda C, Ramalingam V, Chung JH. HRCT evaluation of patients with interstitial lung disease: comparison of the 2018 and 2011 diagnostic guidelines. Ther Adv Respir Dis. 2020 Jan-Dec;14:1753466620968496. doi: 10.1177/1753466620968496. PMID: 33121391; PMCID: PMC7607720. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33121391/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68054"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"261"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68054"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-31T21:11:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-31T21:12:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"261"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82994"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medici